<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1907-03-20T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1907-03-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="148" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d148">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 4992/3.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Rockhill</persName>
                                to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1907-03-20"><hi rend="italic">March 20,
                                1907</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>(Mr. Rockhill states that the Chinese Government in reply to inquiry says
                            that “all American criminals guilty of an ordinary offense who have
                            taken refuge in Chinese territory, can of course be extradited, except
                            those guilty of political offenses.” Mr. Rockhill adds that the Chinese
                            Government will take action in the case submitted upon a statement of
                            the exact nature of the crime and the presentation of written
                            evidence.)</p>
                    </div>
